China reiterated its commitment to "one country, two systems" for Taiwan, unveiling an anti-secession law that Taiwan strongly opposes.
President Chen condemned Beijing's unilateral move to change the Taiwan Strait's status quo, warning of regional instability.
The law aims to legalize a potential military invasion of Taiwan, sparking international concern.
Taiwan fears the law's ambiguous definition of secessionist activities could lead to arrests of its citizens visiting the mainland.
The US, EU, and Japan oppose the law, with Taiwan planning a referendum to decide its future relationship with China.
Legislative Yuan plans to pass a resolution against Beijing's anti-secession legislation.
